Arrhythmia/Electrophysiology

Intracardiac Electrogram T-Wave Alternans/Variability Increases Before Spontaneous Ventricular Tachyarrhythmias in Implantable Cardioverter-Defibrillator Patients
A Prospective, Multi-Center Study
Charles Swerdlow, MD; Theodore Chow, MD; Mithilesh Das, MD; Anne M. Gillis, MD; Xiaohong Zhou, MD; Athula Abeyratne, PhD; Raja N. Ghanem, PhD
Background—T-wave alternans (TWA) increases before ventricular tachycardia (VT) or fibrillation (VF), suggesting that it may warn of VT/VF in implantable cardioverter-defibrillator patients. Recently, we described a method for measuring alternans and nonalternans variability (TWA/V) from electrograms (EGMs) stored in implantable cardioverterdefibrillators before VT/VF. The goal of this prospective, multicenter study was to determine whether EGM TWA/V was greater before VT/VF than at baseline.
Methods and Results—We enrolled 63 implantable cardioverter-defibrillator patients. TWA/V was computed from stored EGMs before spontaneous VT/VF and from sequential windows of 8 pairs of beats using 4 different control recordings: baseline rhythm, rapid pacing at 105 bpm, segments of ambulatory Holter EGMs matched to the time of VT/VF episodes, and EGMs before spontaneous supraventricular tachycardia. During follow-up, 28 patients had 166 episodes of VT/VF. TWA/V was greater before VT/VF (62.9Ϯ3.1 ␮V; nϭ28) than during baseline rhythm (12.8Ϯ1.8 ␮V; PϽ0.0001; nϭ62), during rapid pacing (14.5Ϯ2.0 ␮V; PϽ0.0001; nϭ52), before supraventricular tachycardia (27.5Ϯ6.1 ␮V; PϽ0.0001; nϭ9), or during time-matched ambulatory controls (12.3Ϯ3.5 ␮V; PϽ0.0001; nϭ16). By logistic regression, the odds of VT/VF increased by a factor of 2.2 for each 10-␮V increment in TWA/V (PϽ0.0001).
Conclusions—In implantable cardioverter-defibrillator patients, EGM TWA/V is greater before spontaneous VT/VF than in control recordings. Future implantable cardioverter-defibrillators that measure EGM TWA/V continuously may warn patients and initiate pacing therapies to prevent VT/VF. (Circulation. 2011;123:1052-1060.)
Key Words: implantable cardioverter defibrillator Ⅲ tachyarrhythmias Ⅲ T-wave alternans

B eat-to-beat alternation in duration and amplitude of ventricular action potentials is a form of dynamic electric instability that predisposes to ventricular tachycardia (VT) or ventricular fibrillation (VF).1,2 Alternans2–7 and nonalternating repolarization variability1,7 increases before VT/VF under some conditions.
Clinical Perspective on p 1060
T-wave alternans (TWA), the surface ECG manifestation of action-potential repolarization alternans, is measured to estimate long-term risk of VT/VF.8–10 TWA recorded from intracardiac electrograms (EGMs) of implantable cardioverterdefibrillators (ICDs) correlates well with ECG TWA.11 Investigators have hypothesized that EGM TWA can serve as a predictor of spontaneous VT/VF.4,6,11–14

To test this hypothesis, we developed and validated a method that measures TWA and nonalternans T-wave variability (TWA/V) from ventricular EGMs stored in ICDs before VT/VF.15 Retrospective data indicate that EGM TWA/V is greater before spontaneous VT/VF than in limited baseline recordings15 or after ICD shocks.16 This prospective, multicenter study tested the hypothesis that high-amplitude EGM TWA/V precedes spontaneous VT/VF in ICD patients.
Methods
Each institution obtained approval from its Investigational Research Committee for this prospective, multicenter, nonrandomized study.
Patients
Patients met 4 criteria: (1) They had had a Medtronic ICD implanted for at least 1 month; (2) in the last 3 months, they either had

