Ambulatory recordings were performed for 26 of the 28 patients who had VT/VF during follow-up. Time-matched ambulatory controls could be analyzed for 111 episodes of VT/VF in 16 of these 26 patients (median, 3.5 per patient; range, 1 to 27). TWA/V during these recordings was 12.3Ϯ3.5 ␮V.
Stored preonset EGMs before SVT could be analyzed for 17 episodes in 9 patients. TWA/V was 27.5Ϯ6.1 ␮V. Overall, TWA/V was not statistically different across all types of control recordings (PϾ0.1 for all pairwise comparisons).
TWA/V Before Spontaneous VT/VF Versus Controls Figure 3 shows an example of a preonset EGM before VT and baseline rhythm EGM from an individual patient. The magnitude of TWA/V is much greater in the preonset EGM than in the control EGM.
Comparison of Mean Values Using unpaired comparisons, we found that TWA/V in preonset EGMs before VT/VF (nϭ28) was significantly greater than the

mean values during baseline rhythm controls (nϭ62; PϽ0.0001), rapid-pacing controls (nϭ52; PϽ0.0001), timematched ambulatory controls (nϭ16; PϽ0.0001), or preonset EGMs before SVT (nϭ9; PϽ0.0001). The histogram in Figure 4 shows generalized estimating equation–adjusted proportions of TWA/V measurements as a function of TWA/V amplitude for EGMs before VT/VF and all 4 control data sets.
Using paired comparisons and adjusting for multiple measurements, we compared TWA/V before the 111 VT/VF episodes with time-matched, individual 8-pair control windows in 16 patients. TWA/V was significantly greater in preonset EGMs than controls (51.7Ϯ3.3 versus 10.9Ϯ3.4 ␮V; PϽ0.0001). In addition, with the use of paired comparisons, TWA/V was significantly greater before VT/VF than before SVT (64.7Ϯ3.6 versus 25.6Ϯ5.1 ␮V; PϽ0.0001; nϭ9). Figure 5A shows this comparison on an individual-patient basis.
