Figure 3. Example of T-wave alternans and nonalternans variability (TWA/V) before ventricular tachycardia (VT) and at baseline. A, Preonset electrogram (EGM) before VT shows TWA/V as indicated in the enlarged tracing (beat “a” T wave is larger than beat “b” T wave, except the last pair). B, Baseline EGM in the same patient shows small differences in beatto-beat T-wave amplitudes.

unadjusted and adjusted ROC curves were 0.818 and 0.916, respectively. ROC curve analysis permits optimizing the TWA/V cutoff for a specific performance objective. For example, a threshold of 29.0 ␮V corresponds to an unadjusted specificity of 90% and sensitivity of 61%.
We analyzed a logistic regression model adjusted for multiple episodes per patient that included baseline rhythm controls, rapid-pacing controls, time-matched ambulatory controls, preonset SVT controls, and preonset VT/VF. Greater TWA/V was a significant predictor of VT/VF (PϽ0.0001). The odds of developing VT/VF increased by a factor of 2.2 (95% confidence interval, 2.0 to 2.4; PϽ0.0001) for each 10-␮V increment in TWA/V over the range of TWA/V analyzed (0 to 218 ␮V).
Ventricular Rate During Control Versus Pre-VT/VF Recordings The ventricular rate before VT/VF (nϭ28; 86.2Ϯ2.6 bpm) was faster than that during baseline rhythm controls (nϭ62;

66.3Ϯ1.7 bpm; PϽ0.0001) or time-matched ambulatory controls (nϭ16; 66.9Ϯ3.3 bpm; PϽ0.0001) but slower than that during rapid pacing (nϭ52; 105 bpm) or in EGMs stored before SVT (nϭ9; 132.4Ϯ4.8 bpm; PϽ0.0001).
